<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/EC177B1F-35EE-4B74-981D-E8382EE3D18C"><gtr:id>EC177B1F-35EE-4B74-981D-E8382EE3D18C</gtr:id><gtr:name>London School of Economics &amp; Pol Sci</gtr:name><gtr:department>Social Policy</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Houghton Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Aldwych</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC2A 2AE</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/EC177B1F-35EE-4B74-981D-E8382EE3D18C"><gtr:id>EC177B1F-35EE-4B74-981D-E8382EE3D18C</gtr:id><gtr:name>London School of Economics &amp; Pol Sci</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Houghton Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Aldwych</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC2A 2AE</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/E4690C3F-D7F6-40A8-8877-6910099C0877"><gtr:id>E4690C3F-D7F6-40A8-8877-6910099C0877</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Katerina</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Georgiadis</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH005897%2F1"><gtr:id>EF235C44-70EF-43B9-BBF2-C617587C88F1</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding low fertility in Athens and London: a comparative ethnographic study</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H005897/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This study, conducted between 2003 and 2005, compares the family-formation attitudes and experiences of Greek and British women living in a middle-class area of Athens (Greece) and London (UK) respectively.&amp;nbsp; It takes an inter-disciplinary approach, combining social anthropology, demography and social policy.&amp;nbsp; Findings are based on qualitative research, specifically unstructured and semi-structured interviews, focus groups and participant observation.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The study showed that family building constraints and opportunities (perceived and experienced) in both cities were related to ideas and practices around motherhood and mothering, gendered notions of personhood and identity, childcare arrangements, work-life balance issues and the domestic division of labour.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In Athens, motherhood was described as an 'obligation' or a 'duty' and 'voluntary' childlessness' frowned upon.&amp;nbsp; However, the responsibility to mother clashed with informants' rising aspirations to be 'women'.&amp;nbsp; The difficulty of combining these two experiences was attributed to the government's inadequate support for families.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In London, motherhood was&amp;nbsp; characterised as a 'personal choice' and remaining 'childfree' was seen as acceptable.&amp;nbsp;Yet despite having more support from the government and civil-society organisations, British informants (both working and non-working) described motherhood as a guilt-ridden experience.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The study also compares the Greek and British print media's portrayals of low fertility. &lt;/p>

